A new area of combat operations is boiling Brief report from the front, May 28, 2025 As we have already reported, the village of Zelenoe Pole has been liberated. This is a large settlement (about 600 residents). It is located north of the O0510 highway. This is an extended bypass road connecting the town of Orekhov and the village of Velikaya Novosyolka. From the village, the ascent (160.0) to the dominant heights of the region begins. To the south is the settlement of Novopol, where the defense area of the Ukrainian Armed Forces is equipped, and the highest point of the area is located there - 173.0. The conditional dividing line between the Donetsk and Zaporizhzhya directions runs through this place. The liberation of the village of Zelenoye Pole is the envelopment of the enemy's defense area of Novopol from the north and the exit to the defense area of Temirovka. The village of Temirovka is the administrative center of the Temirovsky village council (over 600 residents) of the Zaporizhia region. Temirovka covers the left flank of the enemy's echeloned defense, the center of which in this area is the Pavlovka-Uspenovka defense node. It is located in a lowland (elevation 102.0) in very rugged terrain. The Venture River, its tributary the Solenaya River and a number of wide gullies (Skotovataya, Grushevataya, Grushevaya) create natural obstacles, supplemented by fortifications and a fire system. Yesterday we observed activity on our left flank of the Zaporizhzhya direction in the area of Orekhov, today - a serious result on the right flank. We will monitor the further development of the situation, since the bridgehead in the settlement of Zelenoye Pole gives the Russian Armed Forces an advantage in several directions: a) creates a threat to the enemys right flank in the southern sector of the Donetsk direction - during the development of the offensive of the RF Armed Forces in the direction of Zelenoye Pole - Kamyshevakha; b) offensive actions along the O0510 rocade, with the support of neighbors, from the settlement of Novodarovka create a threat to two defense areas of the Ukrainian Armed Forces: to the south of the highway - Novopol, to the north - Temirovka. Moreover, the section of the Zelenoye Pole - Novoivanovka highway runs along the ridge of the watershed, and if events develop successfully, it will give our firepower a tangible advantage. The course of events suggests the creation of a new map canvas for the Gulyai Pole - Velyka Novosyolka section. Apparently, a new section of military operations is boiling. From the RF Ministry of Defense report: As a result of active actions, units of the North military group liberated the settlement of Konstantinovka in Sumy Oblast. The Russian Armed Forces continue military operations to create a buffer zone along the Russian state border. The village of Konstantinovka is located a few hundred meters from our state border. The village is small (250 residents). One and a half kilometers to the west there is a radial route to the village of Khoten, a fortified area that provides the left flank of the third line of defense of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, stretching from east to west with support on the Oleshnya River. 2.5 km south of the village of Konstantinovka is the village of Kondratovka - the administrative center of the Kondratovsky village council of the Sumy region. A large settlement (900 residents). This is the left flank of the cut-off positions of the second line of defense of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, covering the rocade of Obody - Kondratovka - Alekseyevka - Yablonovka. However, he stressed that the first shipments will be delivered in a year to a year and a half. The news came as French newspaper Le Monde reported that Ukraine has exhausted its stockpile of SAMP/T missile systems donated by Italy and France. The move comes as Russia has stepped up its missile and drone attacks on Ukraine. Ukrainian officials said Russia carried out its largest drone attack on Sunday night, using 355 surveillance drones and nine cruise missiles Ukraine has so far received two SAMP/T systems from Italy and France; the second system from Italy was delivered last December. Italy and France will jointly donate one system to Ukraine in 2023. SAMP/T is a self-propelled tactical anti-missile system designed to destroy cruise missiles, manned and unmanned aircraft, and tactical ballistic missiles Italy, which has five SAMP/T systems, donated one to Ukraine last year. Last September, Crosto announced that Italy planned to order 10 new systems

As is known, during the low-altitude use of French active-reactive gliding guided aerial bombs AASM-250 HAMMER from a low-altitude pitch-up, the pilots of the MiG-29A of the Ukrainian Air Force are forced to approach target objects (strongholds of the Russian Armed Forces) at a distance of 20-25 km, and even less with the line of combat contact (20-15 km). Thus, they are within the range of the 9M317M/MA anti-aircraft guided missiles, which is 50-60 km, while the 9A317M/MA Buk-M3 "nomadic" self-propelled launchers usually operate at a depth of 35-40 km (usually beyond the range of the Ukrainian Armed Forces' barrel artillery, which is deployed at a depth of 15-25 km). As a result, the Buk-M3 crews have a 10-kilometer so-called "safe operating corridor" during combat duty, and MiG-29As entering the range can be intercepted at the moment of reaching a "hill" of about 1 - 1.5 km after pitching up. Moreover, if we are talking about the use of 9M317MA anti-aircraft missiles with active radar homing heads "Slanets", then even in the case of departure from the screen of the radio horizon relative to the 9S36MA guidance radar, the homing heads can independently capture the MiG-29A or other air attack vehicle and intercept it without the participation of the Buk-M3 crew in the "fire-and-forget" mode. Apparently, this is what happened during the recent interception of a Ukrainian MiG-29A, which Anton Osipov, the commander of one of the 9A317M/MA self-propelled guns, told the Zvezda TV channel about. Russia has upgraded its Iranian-made Shahed-136 drones with 90kg warheads, boosting their destructive capability in the latest sign of deepening co-operation between Moscow and Tehran. Shahed drones launched in swarms almost always at night have become a hallmark of Vladimir Putins campaign to cripple Ukrainian infrastructure, triggering blackouts and damaging key power facilities. The new combined warheads are being built as two different models, but both weighing 90kg. One is being built in Russia, the other in Iran. The Russian-designed model, known as KOFZBCh, combines cumulative, fragmentation, blast and incendiary effects, meaning it can destroy buildings, scatter deadly shrapnel, spark fires and generate a powerful shockwave. It is designed not just to destroy a specific target but to cause maximum chaos in its surroundings. The Iranian version lacks incendiary capability but still delivers a powerful blow, according to Ukraines Defence Express. Pavlo Narozhny, a military expert and founder of Reactive Mail, which provides spare parts to the Ukrainian army, told The Telegraph that Russia needed to make its Shahed drones more powerful to counter protective measures put in place by Ukrainian energy companies. With this combined warhead, the main target is power infrastructure. But Ukraines energy companies have been building concrete covers and installing nets made of steelâ€¦ so Russia needs something to penetrate this infrastructure, Mr Narozhny said He added that while they may be more powerful than standard Shahed-131 and 136 drones, they will need more fuel given their increased weight, making their range much smaller. Shahed 136 drone Earlier this month, Kyiv reported on what was the largest drone attack of the war so far at the time, as Russia launched 273 Shahed drones across Ukraine. The attack included a new jet-powered Geran-3 armed with a 300kg warhead believed to be a Russian clone of the Iranian Shahed-238. Ukrainian air defences intercepted many of the drones, but not all. Several regions, including Kyiv, Dnipropetrovsk and Donetsk, were targeted Tom Withington, a weapons expert at the Royal United Services Institute, said drones guided by fibre-optic cables now used by Moscow and Kyiv are near impossible to jam, highlighting the pace of innovation. Ukraine has been known to attach drones to remote-controlled aircraft to strike oil depots and military targets inside Russia. The attacks are estimated to have disrupted 17 per cent of Russias refining capacity, severely affecting military fuel supplies. Ukraine has also learned how to reconfigure Western-supplied tanks to better hunt enemy drones. The Ukrainian armys 508th Separate Repair and Restoration Battalion is preparing to receive an old German Leopard 1A5 tank modified with a Belgian Cockerill 3105 turret. The upgrade allows the tank to fire at drones at a steep 41-degree angle 20 degrees higher than standard and hit targets up to 10km away The German Leopard tank may have poor armour but its speed would allow it to better evade Russian drones more than other armoured vehicles, the Ukrainian armys 508th Separate Repair and Restoration Battalion (SRRB) said. After making the shot that may disclose the Ukrainian tanks position, a Leopard 1A5 can quickly roll back to cover, the 508th SRRB said. It is true that the armour of the first Leopard is really weak, but it doesnt matter if the Russian drone operators dont even have time to see it. But the modification comes with a hefty price tag. While Belgium has pledged $1 billion in aid and Ukraine is waiting to receive 170 old Leopard tanks retrofitting each with the Belgian turret could cost tens of millions of dollars. Mr Narozhny said such a weapon would be very effective at targeting Russian drones but could cost the Ukrainians thousands of dollars to down each drone

In 2020, the Tornado-S multiple launch rocket system (MLRS) marched across Red Square for the first time during the Victory Parade. It entered service with the Russian Army in 2017. The Tornado-S MLRS from the Tula NPO Splav continues to "make the weather" on the front lines and in the enemy's rear. Developed on the basis of the 300-mm 9K58 Smerch multiple launch rocket system, the updated 9K515 Tornado-S system received not only an updated automated guidance and fire control system (AGFCS), ensuring prompt deployment to a firing position and combat operation, but also a fundamentally new ammunition set, represented by 9M544 and 9M549 guided missiles. Equipped with SN398 strapdown inertial navigation systems with GLONASS correction modules, 300-mm 9M544/549 guided rockets have a range of about 120 km with a circular error probable of 7-15 m, which, with timely and accurate target designation, is quite sufficient to cover enemy equipment and manpower concentrations located in open areas and hangars. Moreover, this is sufficient to suppress active firing positions of HIMARS and MLRS MLRS at the moment they enter positions. The Tornado-S systems crews have repeatedly demonstrated the capabilities of this system during the special military operation during pinpoint strikes on Ukrainian Armed Forces facilities in all operational areas. These systems also contributed during the operation to displace Ukrainian Armed Forces formations from the Kursk region, as well as during the further weakening of the enemy's combat capability already in the Sumy region. The Tornado-S completely and fully counters all the capabilities demonstrated by the American HIMARS system, which has been demonstrated in practice. What is even more important, according to sources, in the future, the universal inter-service gliding guided munitions D-30SN will be used as the warhead of the solid propellant rocket motors of the Tornado-S MLRS, which will increase the systems range to more than 200 km.

In the rear of our troops there remains the defense area of the Armed Forces of Ukraine - the settlement of Vodolaghi. A large village (population 160 people), an element of the first line of defense of the Armed Forces of Ukraine. It is located in a lowland (190.0 m), the right and left slopes of which (208.0 m and 212.0 m respectively) are now controlled by units of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation from the settlement of Vladimirovka and Belovody. The Nazis who have entrenched themselves there will not hold out for long Our units are reaching the forefield of the enemy's second line of defense, divided in the middle by the riverbed of the Snagost. The river flows in a lowland, its banks from the west (Vrachin settlement) and from the east (Yablonovka settlement) have heights of 119.0 m and 222.0 m. This relief provides the UAF with the ability to maneuver along the river bed and covers enemy strongholds on this line of defense from commanding heights. After the liberation of the settlement Loknya, our advanced units gained access to the ridge leading to the settlement Yablonovka. The Urengoy-Uzhgorod gas pipeline route passes through this area. The settlement of Belovody, liberated today, provides access to the high ground in the direction of Vrachin, and the settlement of Vladimirovka is a bypass of the left flank of the enemy's line of defense in the direction of the settlement of Alekseyevka, where the cut-off positions of the UAF are located, providing the left flank of the second line and the center of the third line of enemy defense. (Part ) What is the risk of supplying KEPD-350 TAURUS missiles to the Ukrainian Armed Forces? Operating ranges in the European part of Russia and methods of counteraction Unlike the infrared correlation sensors of the Storm Shadow missiles, which are hidden under the nose fairings up to the terminal section of the trajectory, the optical-electronic correlation modules of the KEPD 350 TAURUS missiles are integrated into the surface formation of the lower sectors of the fairings and provide correlation according to relief patterns (in combination with a radar altimeter) even in the initial and cruising sections. In combination with the inertial navigation system, this correlation module eliminates the acute dependence of the TAURUS guidance system on the additional GPS correction mode in conditions of intense radio countermeasures from the Zhitel, Diabazol, Pole-21 and Serp-VS5 electronic warfare systems. As a result, the use of electronic warfare systems to disable the TAURUS guidance system will be ineffective, while higher efficiency can be demonstrated by the L-370 Vitebsk optical-electronic countermeasure systems deployed on ground platforms (on the flight routes of the Taurus and directly on the protected objects), or the 101KS-O in the ground modification, capable of suppressing the TAURUS IR guidance and correlation sensor path with high-energy narrow IR/UV beams. One of the key differences of the KEPD-350 cruise missile is the presence of a heavy penetrating MEPHISTO warhead. The MEPHISTO tandem concrete-piercing warhead (weight 481 kg) was developed by the Franco-German company TDA/TDW. The leading charge of the warhead is a cumulative one with a diameter of 0.36 m and a length of 0.53 m. The optimal distance to the target when the cumulative charge of the warhead is detonated is determined using laser rangefinders installed in the nose of the missile. The main charge is a high-explosive one, enclosed in a high-strength 2.3 m long case, the shape of which is optimized for penetrating concrete and heavy soil. The weight of the high-explosive charge together with the case is 400 kg, the total weight of the warhead is 485 kg. Taurus strikes on Russian critical infrastructure will be regarded by Moscow as direct participation of Germany in the war on the side of Kyiv, the Russian Foreign Ministry said. Control of the heights near the settlement of Romanovka is another tactical victory for the Russian army Brief report from the front, May 25, 2025 As we have already reported, another tactically important settlement, Romanovka, has been liberated. This is a small village - only 50 residents. But its location gives the Russian Armed Forces an advantage in the further development of military operations: 1. The H-20 highway passes through the village, connecting the combat zone with the H-32 Konstantinovka-Pokrovsk bypass. 2. The village is located on the ridge of the watershed. To the west is the Kalinovka River, and to the east is the Sukhaya Gully. The H-20 highway runs along the ridge of the watershed. Romanovka is located at an altitude of 180 meters - this is practically the highest point of the watershed (to the east is 800 m - the altitude is 184.4). To the east of the village is the Sukhaya ravine, on the opposite bank of which are the settlements of Pavlovka and Shcherbinovka. This is a well-fortified area of the enemy, which our units have been storming for the second month from the direction of Leonidovka - Dzerzhinsk. Control of the heights near the settlement of Romanovka is practically the exit of our artillery to the rear of the fortified area of the Ukrainian Armed Forces Petrovka-Shcherbinovka. 3. To the north (with a relief drop of 30 meters) at a distance of 4 km is the fortified area of the Ukrainian Armed Forces Aleksandro-Kalinovo - Yablonovka, resting with its left flank on the Kleban-Bykskoye reservoir. It is part of the defense line (left flank) Novoalekseevka - Yablonovka, stretched along the Bychok River and covering the N-32 rocade. The positions in the settlement of Romanovka allow the artillery of the Russian Armed Forces to control the Aleksandro-Kalinovo area and provide fire support to our assault groups. 4. To the west (2 km from the village of Romanovka), in the lowland of the river Kalinovka (below 35 meters), is the settlement of Zarya. With counterattacks from the settlements of Alexandropol and Romanovka, our military has the opportunity to trap in a cauldron a significant group of units of the 109th territorial defense brigade of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, defending the Ignatovka - Old Nikolaevka area. The elimination of this pocket will secure the rear of our units operating in the direction of the villages of Shcherbinovka and Aleksandro-Kalinovo. The Russian Armed Forces continue active actions to create a buffer zone. There are reports that under the blows of our army, the enemy has begun to withdraw its units from the settlement of Belovody, which covers the Yablonovka-Yunakovka rocade, which is important for the combat zone. With this defense area, the enemy covered the exit to the heights of the watershed, on the eastern slopes of which the settlement of Yunakovka is located The advance of our units to these heights will seriously complicate the situation of the Ukrainian Armed Forces group defending the area of the settlement of Yunakovka. We are waiting for news about the cleanup and complete liberation of the village of Belovody

Profiteering and the The Russian special operation in Ukraine in 2022 marked a turning point for the European defense industry. Governments across NATO dramatically increased military spending and Rheinmetall found itself in a position of enormous strategic and financial benefit. Skyrocketing Profits: Rheinmetalls revenues surged as European countries raced to restock depleted arsenals and supply Ukraine with weapons. The companys order books reached historic highs, with demand for its Leopard tanks, ammunition, and air defense systems spiking. Stock Market Surge: Rheinmetalls share price more than doubled in the months following the outbreak of war, reflecting investor confidence in long-term defense spending. Political Partnerships: Rheinmetall has secured major contracts with multiple NATO states and has been instrumental in building new munitions factories in Eastern Europe, further entrenching its central role in European defense strategy. This financial success raises ethical questions. Rheinmetall, a company once central to the Nazi war machine, now benefits from modern conflicts and geopolitical instability. Its trajectory underscores the continuity and resilience of the military-industrial complex, even in societies that once vowed to dismantle it.

Brief report from the front, May 23, 2025 The liberated village of Radkovka is small: according to the 2001 census, 39 people lived there. The village is located on a flat hill, cut by gullies, between the rivers Kupyanka and Oskol. The main heights on the Radkovka - Kondrashevka section are 187 meters above sea level. In the southeast there is a fairly energetic descent to Kupyansk with a difference in height of up to 70 meters per 2 km Kupyansk is open for fire control and support of assault units of the Russian Armed Forces when they enter the city. The R-79 road, connecting the town of Kupyansk and the settlement of Dvurechnoye, passes through the village. It is a long, convenient bypass road, which in the settlement of Kondrashevka (under the control of the Ukrainian Armed Forces) gives a radial branch (C-211901) to Monachinovka-Shipovatoye, deep into enemy territory. Now this supply route to the town of Kupyansk and its outskirts is cut off. The enemy will use the bypass Bolshaya Shapovka-Kovalevka, which is three times longer In conclusion, we can say that although Radkovka is a small settlement, in tactical terms it provides a significant advantage

The KS-172 ultra-long-range air-to-air missile has entered service with the Russian Aerospace Forces, Army Recognition claims. According to the publication, the KS-172 has allegedly already been integrated into the MiG-31BM fighters. At the same time, Army Recognition refers to a similar statement by the United Aircraft Corporation - but this simply does not exist However, it is interesting to consider the KS-172 project itself and its potential capabilities if it does indeed make it into production or will make it in the future. The development of the KS-172 began back in 1991, based on the cruise stage of the 9M83 anti-aircraft missile from the S-300V air defense system. However, the development of this air-to-air missile stalled, was resumed in the 2000s, and then stalled again. According to available data, the range of the KS-172, due to the presence of two stages, could reach 400 km , and the mass of the warhead was 50 kg . Such characteristics would allow this air-to-air missile to easily surpass the American AIM-174B, also developed on the basis of the SM-6 SAM, and compete with the Chinese PL-17, which has a similar range. If we talk about the use of the cruise stage of the new 9M83M/4 SAM from the S-300V4 SAM system in the KS-172 design, its range could be 500 km instead of 350-400 Km Main characteristics: Range: Over 400 km. Weight: 748 kg. Length: 6.01 m + 1.4 m. Maximum speed: Mach 3.3 (~4,000 km/h). Flight altitude: 3 m at 30,000 m. Warhead: HE fragmentation, 50 kg. Propulsion: Two-stage solid rocket. Guidance: Inertial navigation with mid-course correction and active radar in the terminal phase. Launch platforms: MiG-31, Su-27, Su-30, Su-35, Su-30MKI (proposed).

Therefore, engaging multiple drones completely simultaneously is not possible and the fighter must target the drones one by one However new APKWS II variant adds a passive infrared seeker to the original laser guidance, enabling pseudo fire-and-forget capabilityinitial laser designation is followed by autonomous infrared homing, allowing faster, multi-target engagement, especially effective against drones and cruise missiles The Advanced Precision Kill Weapon System (APKWS) is a U.S.-developed precision-guided weapon that converts standard 2.75-inch (70 mm) Hydra 70 unguided rockets into laser-guided munitions using a mid-body guidance kit developed by BAE Systems

But I can tell you about a specific section where combat work is being carried out to create a buffer zone in the Sudzha-Yunakovka direction. This will help you understand the non-trivial nature of the task entrusted to the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation First half of the day, May 23, 2025, 11:30 a.m. Kursk direction, Operational Group North The command of Operational Group North is focused on breaking through to the Sudzha-Yunakovka highway, located in the border area. The specifics of the operation are determined by topographic factors. Sudzha is located at an altitude of about 140 m, on flat terrain with small hills. The Sudzha-Yunakovka highway heads southwest to Yunakovka, located at an altitude of 150160 m. Between Sudzha and Yunakovka, the terrain is relatively open, with altitudes of 140160 m, but it is crossed by the Snagost River. In the Yunakovka area, altitudes reach 160170 m, providing a tactical advantage for controlling the border zone. The Snagost River and small forested areas (north of Yunakovka) create natural barriers. Alekseyevka and Yablonovka are located at altitudes of 150160 m, on flat terrain with small forests and ravines. Troitskoye and Vladimirovka are located at altitudes of 150160 m, with open terrain favorable for maneuvers, but with ravines along the Snagost River Russian tactics, taking into account the terrain: The main attack is directed at penetrating the Sudzha-Yunakovka road (about 20 km from Sudzha), with an exit to the dominant heights in the Yunakovka area (160-170 m). These heights allow control of the supply routes and expansion of the bridgehead to the east, north, and northwest of Yunakovka. An offensive along the Snagost River (on both banks) requires forcing the river, which makes armored maneuvers difficult due to the possibility of swampy areas. A simultaneous exit to the Alekseyevka-Yablonovka line involves envelopment from the north. A secondary attack through Troitskoye-Vladimirovka uses open terrain for maneuvers, but ravines along the Snagost River may slow the advance. Drones (UAVs) play a key role in height reconnaissance and fire adjustment, especially in the Yunakovka area, where the heights give the enemy a defensive advantage. FPV drones carry out precise strikes against fortifications, but the forests north of Yunakovka limit their visibility. Risks arise from the hydrography of the Snagost River, where swampy areas create natural barriers that make crossing and maneuvering difficult for armored vehicles. The open terrain between Sudzha and Yunakovka (altitude 140 to 160 m) facilitates the use of drones, but makes forces vulnerable to Ukrainian counterattacks, especially through electronic warfare, as has been reported in the Kursk Oblast border area. The Ukrainian Armed Forces can use small forested areas and ravines along Snagost to conduct ambushes and deploy weapons against infantry and light vehicles. Electronic warfare in the Yunakovka area, where the Armed Forces of Ukraine have likely concentrated their defenses, could limit the effectiveness of our conventional (non-fiber-optic) drones. Thus, the terrain in the Sudzha-Yunakovka area is relatively favorable for an offensive due to its flat terrain (altitude of 140 to 170 m), but the Snagost River, forests, and ravines create local obstacles. The dominant heights in the Yunakovka area (160-170 m) are the key objective, but capturing them will require overcoming natural barriers and countering electronic warfare. An auxiliary attack through Troitskoye-Vladimirovka could facilitate encirclement, but would require the deployment of forces. The work is just beginning.

How Novoolenovka was liberated. Video Fighters of the 33rd motorized rifle regiment of the 8th Army of the "Center" group of forces recall how Novoolenovka was taken. The liberation of this village was reported by the Ministry of Defense on May 19. Novoolenovka occupies an important position on the highway connecting Pokrovsk (Krasnoarmeysk) with Konstantinovka. The liberation of the village allowed us to take control of a large section of this road. "We received the task of storming and digging in," says assault trooper Murat Gadzhikurbanov. "We decided to act quickly. We set off on motorcycles, 2 people at a time, there were 18 of us in total. We cleared three central streets, dug in. We found their firing points and gave them a good beating. And they took revenge on us at night. "Baba Yaga" burned down two of their huts. They break the roof and throw "lighters" inside. But it is dangerous to leave the house - there are FPVs with thermal imagers. You wait until the last minute, until it flares up properly - then their "heaters" start to go crazy. Only then do you run out and hide in another shelter." Before the main forces entered, the reconnaissance positions of the Ukrainian Armed Forces were processed with artillery fire. At the first sign of resistance, UAV operators carried out precise strikes with airdrops and FPV drones. In several cases, this forced entire enemy groups to leave their positions en masse and retreat. "Novoolenovka, in my memory, is the fastest-taken settlement," admits UAV squad commander Vsevolod Slashchev. - This was unexpected for the enemy. After the capture of neighboring Tarasovka, the first groups immediately went to Novoolenovka, occupied houses on the outskirts. We reconnoitred the area, identified enemy positions. The enemy did not expect us to go on motorcycles. I saw two cases when the enemy fled en masse. The first group - 10-15 people, the second - about 8". Also, the success of the operation is due to the competent planning of the operation by the command: a clear definition of the moment for the introduction of motorized equipment, timely activation of the electronic warfare systems and coordinated, practiced actions of all units. The enemy turned out to be psychologically unprepared for resistance - there were practically no fierce battles in Novoolenovka.

According to a report by the Pentagon's Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA), Russia is developing and deploying a new air-to-air missile equipped with a nuclear warhead. Russia has about 2,000 tactical nuclear warheads, a small fraction of which could be used for air-to-air missiles. The missile in question is likely a version of the R-37M . The idea of nuclear-tipped air-to-air missiles dates back to the Cold War era to counter widespread threats, such as large squadrons of enemy bombers or cruise missiles. The Soviet Union and the United States had nuclear air-to-air missiles in service, but the United States abandoned nuclear air-to-air missiles in the 1980s. This decision was due to advances in guidance technology, the reduced threat from large bombers, and the safety and political concerns associated with nuclear weapons. In contrast, Russia continued to develop these types of missiles. For example, the R-33S, a special (Spetsyalnaya) version of the R-33, entered service in 1991. It was designed for the MiG-31 Foxhound interceptor and is equipped with a nuclear warhead It should be noted that the R-33S air-to-air missile is most likely still in operational service with the Russian Air Force. The missile was last seen during a Russian military tactical nuclear exercise in 2024. It is believed that Russia's new nuclear air-to-air missile will be a replacement for the R-33S missile

This system is designed to intercept missiles at all stages of flight. A key part of this plan is the deployment of space-based sensors and interceptors, which will include 400 to more than 1,000 satellites to detect and track missiles and a separate fleet of 200 missile or laser-equipped attack satellites. This network could destabilize global security by weakening the nuclear deterrent of rival states and encourage powers like China and Russia to build more missiles and nuclear warheads to overcome the shield. This could lead to an arms race, as offensive missiles are usually cheaper to produce than defensive interceptors. Deploying weapons in space could also heighten tensions, as rivals could develop anti-satellite capabilities or orbital nuclear warheads to neutralize Golden Dome satellites. China and Russia have called the plan highly destabilizing and warned of an arms race in space. Experts believe that thousands of interceptors (perhaps 16,000) would be needed to counter even a small number of ICBMs. Satellites are vulnerable to attack, and the system could be overwhelmed by simultaneous launches or the use of decoys. The huge cost of the project could strain the United States and divert resources from other priorities, such as modernizing the Air Force's intercontinental ballistic missiles. Democrats are critical of the bidding process, especially the role of SpaceX, led by Trump ally Elon Musk. SpaceX is leading the way in collaborating with two other companies for the "surveillance layer" of reconnaissance and tracking satellites, building on its Starlink experience. Finally; the project was initially called "Iron Dome for America", but was renamed Golden Dome to avoid confusion with the Israeli system, which is for short-range threats

Donald Trump unveils Golden Dome missile defense program US President Donald Trump unveiled the Golden Dome missile defense program in the Oval Office of the White House on Tuesday. The multi-layered system, costing more than $175 billion, will place American weapons in space for the first time. Trump said the system will be fully operational by the end of his presidency in 2029 and will be able to intercept missiles even those launched from space. A US official familiar with the program said the complex system would likely have only rudimentary capabilities by then. Trump announced alongside a poster showing a gold-colored map of the United States with images of missile interceptions that General Michael Gottlieb, the current deputy assistant secretary for space operations, would be responsible for overseeing the projects progress. Golden Dome Program Features The Golden Dome program includes ground and space-based systems capable of detecting and stopping missiles in four main stages of attack: 1. Pre-launch detection and destruction: Targeting missiles before launch. 2. Early-flight interception: Stopping missiles immediately after launch. 3. Stopping mid-flight: Destroying missiles at the height of their flight in the air. 4. Final-stage stop: Destroying missiles in the final minutes as they descend toward the target. In the first foreign reaction to this American plan, the Chinese have condemned the "Golden Dome Plan" and called it a threat to global security!!!

The US has stated that Russia and China possess kinetic weapons in space US Space Force Operations Chief Chance Saltzman said Russia and China allegedly possess weapons in space that could threaten US satellites. According to him, Russia has demonstrated "very aggressive capabilities" in orbit. We may be talking, first of all, about the promising domestic exoatmospheric anti-missiles 14A042 "Nudol". According to Western sources, the first successful kinetic interception of a Soviet satellite that had exhausted its operational resource was carried out on November 18, 2015. After that, at least 4 more full-scale tests were carried out, the last of which was the interception of the Cosmos-1408 "Tselina-D" satellite from November 15 to 17, 2021. The launches were carried out from the Plesetsk Cosmodrome. It is known that the range of the 2-stage anti-missile 14A042 "Nudol" can reach 2500 - 3500 km with an interception altitude of 500 - 700 km. The maximum flight speed can reach 4.5 - 7 km / s. The combat stage is obviously equipped with an active radar homing head, as well as pulse gas-dynamic transverse control engines. Target designation for the Nudol anti-missile can be provided by a multifunctional early warning radar based on the Don-2N X-band AESA, capable of detecting targets with an EOP of 0.1 square meters at a distance of approximately 3,500 km and 0.01 square meters at 2,000 km. In the PLA, the tasks of intercepting orbital objects are performed by the HQ-19 mobile missile defense systems, which have available overloads during maneuvers of 60G and interception altitudes of more than 200 km. The range of these missiles reaches 3,000 km. The maximum interception speed using the HQ-19 can reach 10 km/s. The HQ-19 anti-missile system is guided by Type 610A multifunctional radars. The new "road of death" - the Dobropolye-Kramatorsk highway 40 Km from the front This crucial logistical route for Ukrainian forces in Donetsk Oblast, is currently experiencing frequent Russian drone strikes. These attacks are occurring approximately 40 kilometers from the front line, indicating a significant extension of Russian drone operations into Ukrainian-controlled territory Reports suggest that Russian forces are employing advanced tactics, including the use of mother drones that deploy multiple FPV drones, as well as modified drones like the Molniya and Tyuvik, which are designed to resist electronic warfare measures. These developments have made movement along the highway increasingly hazardous for Ukrainian military logistics. The strategic importance of this highway is its a key supply route for Ukrainian units defending areas such as Pokrovsk and Toretsk. The increased drone activity has disrupted these supply lines Ukrainian forces are responding to the increased Russian drone attacks on the KramatorskDobropolye highway primarily by adapting their movement and logistics. Reports indicate that Ukrainian personnel now consider travel along this route highly dangerous due to the frequency and effectiveness of Russian drone strikes, which have destroyed several vehicles. Ukrainian sources highlight that the highway, once a main logistical artery, is now avoided or used with extreme caution There are no detailed reports in the search results of specific new countermeasures on this highway, such as deploying additional air defenses or electronic warfare systems in this area. However, Ukrainian forces across the front have been known to use camouflage, movement at night, and dispersal tactics to reduce losses from drone attacks. Ukrainian drone teams are also actively conducting their own strikes against Russian forces elsewhere in Donetsk, using surveillance and FPV drones to target Russian infantry and positions In summary, Ukrainian forces are limiting movement on the KramatorskDobropolye highway and relying on standard counter-drone tactics, but the road remains highly vulnerable to Russian drone operations

The Russian army is preparing to organize decisive actions in the direction of Pokrovsk and Konstantinovka Brief report from the front, May 19, 2025 Message from the Russian Ministry of Defense: As a result of active and decisive actions by units of the Center group of forces, the settlement of Novoolenovka in the Donetsk Peoples Republic has been liberated. The development of the offensive of the Russian Armed Forces on the right flank of the Pokrovsk direction, at the junction with the Dzerzhinsky section, continues. Actions in this area provide offensive maneuvers on the fortified areas of the Ukrainian Armed Forces Pokrovsk and Konstantinovka. Having broken through the first two lines of defense of the Ukrainian Armed Forces and outflanked them, units of the Russian Armed Forces began to destroy the third line on the Popov Yar - Aleksandro-Kalinovo line. It can be assumed that pressure on this line of defense will be carried out by flanking envelopments along the N-32 (Novoolenovka-Konstantinovka) and N-20 (Romanovka-Konstantinovka) highways. Trying to stop the threat of bypassing the city of Pokrovsk from the east (by our right flank), the enemy began transferring reserves from the Bogatyr region and the central section of the Pokrovsk direction. We had previously assumed that the lack of time and operational reserves would force the enemy to maneuver units at the tactical level, exposing areas of defense in the main direction. And so it turned out. The 38th separate marine brigade of the Ukrainian Armed Forces moved from the Pokrovsk area to the reserve accumulation lines (Rodinskoye - Novotoretskoye - Vladimirovka). Units of the corps of operational-surprise action of the national police of Ukraine "KORD" arrived from the Bogatyr area. And the 36th separate marine brigade of the Ukrainian Armed Forces was transferred from the Sumy region to the area of the settlement Popov Yar. All these directions (Bogatyr, Pokrovsk center, Sumy region) are very hot, and the Russian Armed Forces are pushing back the Ukrainian Armed Forces in all these directions. Nevertheless, motivated and relatively combat-ready units have been withdrawn from there and sent to mitigate the threat in the Pokrovsk-Konstantinovka area. Apparently, in the coming days the Russian Ministry of Defense will announce the liberation of the settlements of Malinovka and Novaya Poltavka. The Russian Armed Forces are moving to their initial positions to organize decisive actions in the direction of the main fortified areas: Pokrovsk and Konstantinovka. We expect that the Chasov Yar section will become more active in the near future. To our fighters - success, determination and victory!

The Russian Armed Forces are preparing to enter the Turya settlement line Brief report from the front, May 19, 2025 As reported by the Russian Ministry of Defense: As a result of decisive actions, units of the North military group liberated the settlement of Maryino in the Sumy region. In mid-March 2025, the Ukrainian Armed Forces launched a new provocation on the border with Russia. They attempted to break through the state border at the junction of two Russian regions - Kursk and Belgorod. The terrain in this area is very rugged - with deep ravines and gullies. The enemy planned, using the folds of the terrain, to secretly reach the attack lines and capture the settlements of Popovka, Demidovka, Prilesye. Thereby creating a bridgehead for further advancement deep into the territory of the Russian Federation. However, in the first days of the provocation, the RF Armed Forces launched complex fire strikes against the advancing enemy units, dispersed them, and began clearing the territories where individual disparate groups of the Ukrainian Armed Forces were able to enter. Over the course of three weeks, the enemy's sabotage and reconnaissance groups were destroyed in the village of Popovka. Today our advanced units entered the territory of Sumy Oblast and liberated the village of Maryino. The village is small, according to the 2001 census, 58 families lived there. It is located on a stream - a tributary of the river Gryaznaya, downstream 3 km is the Russian village of Grafovka. The village of Maryino is located in a lowland, which is surrounded by dominant heights (the main one is 223 m). At a distance of 3.5 kilometers to the southwest is the village of Turya - the administrative center of the Turyansky village council. The village of Tur'ya is located in a lowland, at the source of the river Gryaznaya. The village is surrounded by heights: from the northwest height 234.2, to the southeast height 221 and in the southwest height 231.8. These are the highest points of the area. The area is very convenient for monitoring the surrounding area and provides covert maneuver and logistics along deep ravines and along the river bed. Reaching the Turya settlement line will provide the Russian Armed Forces units with control over the center of the enemy group's location area. The village of Maryino is connected by a dirt road (running west of the village) with the village of Turya and the settlement of Ugroedy. To ensure access to the Turya line, our units must secure the right flank - liberate the settlement of Prokhody, where the main units of the 225th separate assault regiment of the Armed Forces of Ukraine are concentrated, covering the fork in the road network in this area. It can be assumed that the further target of our command will be the settlement of Prokhody.

The enemy's defense in the area of the strongholds Bogatyr - Dachnoye - Alekseyevka is cracking at the seams Brief report from the front, May 18, 2025 Activity of the Russian Armed Forces is observed along the entire length of the Donetsk direction LBS: from the city of Dzerzhinsk to the village of Bogatyr. On the northern front (Dzerzhinsk) there are active actions along the Druzhba-Konstantinovka railway. The Dyleevka railway station is being stormed. Further south, at the junction of the Pokrovsky and Konstantinovsky sections, advance towards the settlement of Romanovka, located on the N-20 road. The Ukrainian Armed Forces' network of strongholds in the Gnatovka-Zarya-Staraya Nikolaevka area is cut off from supplies. This area will most likely come under the control of the Russian Armed Forces in the coming days. At the same time, the possibility of our assault groups reaching the rear of the Shcherbinovka-Petrovskoye area, about 4 km in a straight line, appears. According to all forecasts, the LBS will soon align along the Alexandropol-Shcherbinovka line. We are moving along the line of clashes to the west, where the right flank of the Pokrovsky direction has become active. Assault groups of the Russian Armed Forces have consolidated their positions on the outskirts of the settlement of Novaya Poltavka and have advanced north to the east of the settlement of Malinovka, enveloping the network of strongholds in the Novaya Poltavka area from the west and creating a threat of encirclement. In this way, they are forcing the enemy to retreat northward. On the left side of the salient remains the settlement of Malinovka, cut off from interaction with the group of units of the Ukrainian Armed Forces in Novaya Poltavka. Both enemy fortified areas (Malinovka and Novaya Poltavka) are under threat of flank attacks. Message from the Russian Ministry of Defense: "Servicemen of the 29th Guards Combined Arms Army of the Vostok group of forces, during active offensive operations, liberated the settlement of Bogatyr in the South Donetsk direction, unfurling Russian flags." This is a serious blow to the enemys defense in the southern section of the Donetsk direction. The area of the Bogatyr-Dachnoe-Alekseevka strongholds is the main obstacle after the destruction of the Ulakly-Konstantinovka-Andreevka area. After liberating the settlement of Bogatyr, we consider the enemy's defense in this area to be broken through, the next target for efforts is Alekseyevka. The elimination of this area allows us, without fear for the right flank, covering the flank of the Volchya River, to reach the settlement of Komar along the road, enveloping the enemy's defense area Otradnoye-Komar-Fedorovka from the north As a result, we see how the tactics of small cuts and the dispersal of enemy reserves along the entire line yields tangible results

Russian President Vladimir Putin addressed journalists after a phone conversation with U.S. President Donald Trump, describing the more than two-hour-long discussion as significant, sincere, and highly constructive. Putin said he expressed gratitude to Trump for the United States involvement in efforts to restore direct negotiations between Moscow and Kyiv. He reiterated Russias position that hostilities must come to an end, while emphasizing the need to identify the most effective path toward a lasting peace. A temporary ceasefire in Ukraine, he noted, would only be possible if concrete and appropriate agreements are reached. The Russian leader added that Moscow is prepared to work on drafting a memorandum with Ukraine, which would include, among other things, a cessation of hostilities. Putin underlined the importance of reaching compromises acceptable to all parties involved.

For the first time in almost the entire period of operation, we can delight the eye with high-quality footage of the aerobatics of the heavy carrier-based multi-role fighter Su-33 from the 279th separate naval fighter aviation regiment based at the Severomorsk-3 airfield, part of which was initially stationed on board the TAVKR Project 1143.5 Admiral Kuznetsov until it was put in for repairs on May 20, 2022. The aerobatics were carried out as part of exercises involving the practice of air combat and interception of enemy UAVs together with the crew of the Su-30SM multi-role fighter of the Russian Navys naval aviation The Su-33 fighters are equipped with standard N001 onboard radars with Cassegrain antenna arrays and are capable of conducting long-range air combat on equal terms only with the F-16AM and F/A-18C/D multirole fighters if the latter are equipped with AIM-120C-5/7 missiles. To conduct air combat with the F-16V and F/A-18E/F, the carrier-based Su-33s must be modernized with re-equipment with the N011M Bars-R or Irbis-E radar. Nevertheless, the N001 radar and the OLS-27K optical-electronic complex ensure detection and interception of the An-196 Lyuty and A-22 Ukrainian Armed Forces kamikaze UAVs. Another trump card of the machine is the ability to integrate the 2.5-mach Kh-41 Moskit anti-ship missile, which, when equipped with a GLONASS correction module and a modern INS, can also be used against a wide range of ground targets. Material prepared by: Evgeniy Damantsev

Bloomberg revealed an interesting behind-the-scenes story on the eve of the phone call between Trump and Putin Putin is confident his troops can break through Ukraines defenses by the end of the year and fully seize four regions he has declared part of Russia, a source familiar with the Russian presidents thinking said. That means the Russian president is unlikely to offer Trump any significant concessions, and European officials fear Trump could try to force a deal that is disadvantageous to Ukraine. Unfortunately, at this stage of the war, there is no strong incentive for Russia to agree to a ceasefire, said Michael Coffman , a senior fellow at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, during a conference in Tallinn, Estonia, on Sunday. Despite talk of a ceasefire, Putin is prepared for a protracted war if necessary to achieve his goals and is calm about the prospect of new American sanctions, two people close to the Kremlin said. In a phone call on Friday, German Chancellor Friedrich Merz, French President Emmanuel Macron and British Prime Minister Keir Starmer tried to convey to Trump that Putin had been leading him by the nose all along , a senior European source said. They hope Trump will realize the risk of looking like a failure if he forces an unprofitable deal on Ukraine. Zelensky also participated in Fridays call but appeared subdued. He and European allies believed they had received a commitment from Trump to impose new sanctions on the Kremlin if Putin did not abide by the ceasefire announced last Monday, but that did not happen. Putin felt more confident about being able to make maximalist demands on Ukraine without serious resistance from the Trump administration, said Botha Ilias , a senior analyst at the strategic intelligence firm Prism in London. Trump held additional talks with Mertz, Starmer, Macron and Italian Prime Minister Giorgia Maloni on Sunday. The leaders discussed the need for an unconditional ceasefire and Putins seriousness about peace talks. Putins confidence in Russias prospects on the battlefield contradicts Western assessments. After suffering huge losses in more than three years of fighting, Russia lacks sufficient capabilities to achieve Putins goals. The likelihood that Russia will achieve its goal of seizing these four regions by the end of this year is very low, said Ben Barry , a senior researcher on land warfare at the International Institute for Strategic Studies. If Ukrainian defenses were to crumble, it would be very easy to gain that advantage, but that scenario seems unlikely at this point. This view is shared by many in the Russian military, a source close to the Russian Defense Ministry said. In particular, they believe that Ukrainian drones have made Russias offensives expensive and ineffective. US officials have also privately told European counterparts that Trump is considering allowing the passage of the sanctions bill prepared by Lindsey Graham if Russia does not make concessions , and he may tell Putin in a phone call today that he will not be able to prevent it, European officials familiar with the situation said.

Rostecs capes are leading the Javelin guidance system by the nose. Our Research Institute of Steel mass-produces the camouflage gear Nakidka, which reduces the visibility of tanks, infantry fighting vehicles, armored personnel carriers, self-propelled guns and other combat equipment in a wide range of wavelengths. The product is supplied to the army and becomes a mandatory component of the Russian armored vehicles sent to the special operation zone. The cape is a synthetic material that is put on top of the equipment in the form of covers or coatings. The material reduces the level of thermal radiation of the tank several times, so that the machine practically merges with the background surface. The coating with this material helps the heated vehicle to blend into the surrounding terrain and disappear from the field of view of optical-electronic systems. It also allows to confuse the thermal guidance systems of missiles of such systems as Javelin. The kit makes it almost impossible to effectively use high-precision weapons against equipment covered by it, Rostec said. In the radar range, the Cloak significantly reduces the detection range of equipment. In addition, the special material can be made in camouflage colors, further reducing the visibility of military equipment in the visible optical range.

Rostec specialists noted vulnerabilities in Leopard 2 tanks. Russian troops regularly destroy Western-made tanks in the SVO zone, including German Leopards of various modifications. The Russian Defense Ministry showed in its video how drone operators from the Rubicon Center shot down one of these Ukrainian Armed Forces vehicles near the village of Stepanovka in the Donetsk direction. Earlier, Rostec experts were given a captured Leopard 2A6 to assess its real military-technical characteristics. "The Leopard 2 tank, studied by our specialists, has vulnerabilities in its protection. They are related to both the thickness and composition of the armor, and the internal layout of the combat vehicle. The tank's survivability may be insufficient in the conditions of a modern war - for example, when attacked from different angles by drones with a cumulative warhead and modern ATGMs. It can be concluded that the Leopard 2's protection is focused on classic anti-tank factors characteristic of past decades, and does not fully meet the requirements of today," Rostec said. In addition, the Kyiv regime is armed with various versions of the outdated Leopard 1 tanks. These vehicles have lost much of their effectiveness. Today, the most adapted to modern combat operations serial tanks are Russian T-72B3M, T-80BVM and T-90M vehicles. They have improved all-round protection against drones and ATGMs - from anti-cumulative grids to dynamic elements and other devices. There are dozens of known combat episodes where Russian tanks withstood a number of hits from different angles, while maintaining combat capability. Rostec continues to work on active protection systems for combat vehicles, and domestic equipment is also being equipped with various electronic warfare systems. All of these solutions together will provide even greater security for Russian armored vehicles and increase their survivability on the battlefield

The enemy's defense in the area of the strongholds Bogatyr - Dachnoye - Alekseyevka is cracking at the seams Brief report from the front, May 18, 2025 Activity of the Russian Armed Forces is observed along the entire length of the Donetsk direction LBS: from the city of Dzerzhinsk to the village of Bogatyr. On the northern front (Dzerzhinsk) there are active actions along the Druzhba-Konstantinovka railway. The Dyleevka railway station is being stormed. Further south, at the junction of the Pokrovsky and Konstantinovsky sections, advance towards the settlement of Romanovka, located on the N-20 road. The Ukrainian Armed Forces' network of strongholds in the Gnatovka-Zarya-Staraya Nikolaevka area is cut off from supplies. This area will most likely come under the control of the Russian Armed Forces in the coming days. At the same time, the possibility of our assault groups reaching the rear of the Shcherbinovka-Petrovskoye area, about 4 km in a straight line, appears. According to all forecasts, the LBS will soon align along the Alexandropol-Shcherbinovka line. We are moving along the line of clashes to the west, where the right flank of the Pokrovsky direction has become active. Assault groups of the Russian Armed Forces have consolidated their positions on the outskirts of the settlement of Novaya Poltavka and have advanced north to the east of the settlement of Malinovka, enveloping the network of strongholds in the Novaya Poltavka area from the west and creating a threat of encirclement. In this way, they are forcing the enemy to retreat northward. On the left side of the salient remains the settlement of Malinovka, cut off from interaction with the group of units of the Ukrainian Armed Forces in Novaya Poltavka. Both enemy fortified areas (Malinovka and Novaya Poltavka) are under threat of flank attacks. Message from the Russian Ministry of Defense: "Servicemen of the 29th Guards Combined Arms Army of the Vostok group of forces, during active offensive operations, liberated the settlement of Bogatyr in the South Donetsk direction, unfurling Russian flags." This is a serious blow to the enemys defense in the southern section of the Donetsk direction. The area of the Bogatyr-Dachnoe-Alekseevka strongholds is the main obstacle after the destruction of the Ulakly-Konstantinovka-Andreevka area. After liberating the settlement of Bogatyr, we consider the enemy's defense in this area to be broken through, the next target for efforts is Alekseyevka. The elimination of this area allows us, without fear for the right flank, covering the flank of the Volchya River, to reach the settlement of Komar along the road, enveloping the enemy's defense area Otradnoye-Komar-Fedorovka from the north. As a result, we see how the tactics of small cuts and the dispersal of enemy reserves along the entire line yields tangible results

The enemy's defenses continue to be fragmented in a focal manner in the Pokrovsky direction. Today there is increased activity on the demarcation line between the Pokrovsky and Konstantinovsky directions. Alexandropol is located at an altitude of 196 meters above sea level. The highest point in this area is height 221 (west of the settlement Zarya). The Russian Armed Forces reach the watershed (the interfluve of the Bychok and Kalinovka rivers). To the east, along the ridge of the watershed of the Kalinovka and Skelevaya ravine, there is an interesting road Aleksandro-Kalinovo - Romanovka - Sukhaya Balka It is interesting because for the right flank of the Pokrovsky direction it is radial, and for the left flank of the Konstantinovsky direction it is a rocade. The exit of our strike units to the settlement of Zarya will allow us to control this road along its entire length from the fork with the N-32 (to the north) to the settlement of Romanovka This is a real problem for enemy groups defending the Aleksandro-Kalinovo - Romanovka areas and west of Dzerzhinsk This wedge is dangerous for the Ukrainian Armed Forces because it gives the Russian Armed Forces operational freedom in choosing actions, both in the direction to the west (threatening the Pokrovsk fortified area from the east) and in the direction to the east, forming a coverage of the Aleksandro-Kalinovo - Kleban-Byk area (the forefield of the city of Konstantinovka). The enemy will be forced to pull up reserves to stop the threat. This can be done operationally only by withdrawing some forces from the city of Chasov Yar or from its right flank of the Pokrovsk direction. The Yolka is a Russian-developed kinetic interceptor drone designed specifically to neutralize enemy drones through direct, non-explosive collisions. Its primary function is to intercept and physically disable hostile UAVs, such as those used by Ukraine, by ramming into them mid-air with high precision Challenge Addressed: Cheap, mass-produced Ukrainian UAVs overwhelm costly air-defense missiles and expose static launch platforms to enemy fire Solution: A compact capture-fire-forget interceptor that destroys targets via high-speed collisionno explosive warhead needed Performance: Highly maneuverable, AI-assisted tracking delivers a very high hit rate against FPV strike drones (Baba Yaga), recon UAVs, etc Ease of Use: Simple reusable launcher and minimalist operator procedure allow frontline troops to deploy Yolka quickly and safely. Safety & Cost: Kinetic interception eliminates onboard explosives, reducing risk to personnel and lowering per-shot cost versus missiles Future Development: Plans include fully automated air-defense systems for large military and industrial sites, minimizing human oversight The images are from tests carried out last September.

Important maneuvers on the flanks Brief report from the front, May 16, 2025 Pokrovskoe direction The presented diagram of the central section of the Pokrovsky direction shows the configuration of the LBS as of May 16, 2025. The first ten days of May are marked by the activity of the right flank of the sector: the settlements of Mirolyubovka and Mikhailovka have been liberated, the initial area for developing the offensive on Novoekonomichnoe, where the logistics hub of the Ukrainian Armed Forces is located, connecting (by the N-32 road) the enemy's flanks. The exit to this hub will reduce the enemy's maneuver arm. The left flank of the central section was in deep defense for almost the entire month of April. The initiative belonged to the enemy, who tried to cut off the Kotlino salient formed by the offensive actions of the RF Armed Forces with flank attacks from Pokrovsk-Shevchenko and Muravka-Uspenovka. Having exhausted the Ukrainian Armed Forces in defensive battles and stretched out their reserves, our army began to carefully press on the enemys right flank, and in the first third of May the settlements of Troitskoye, Kotlyarovka, Novoalexandrovka, and earlier Uspenovka were liberated. Today, the most problematic area is Kotlyarovka-Pokrovskaya mine, where the enemy has set up a well-fortified defensive area. With access to the Pokrovskaya mine, the left flank of our group will secure the reference point for encircling Pokrovsk from the west. Based on the configuration of the LBS, we see and understand the tactical task: cutting off the enemys logistics on the H-32 highway on the western and eastern shoulders of logistics. I dont think that the negotiations taking place in Istanbul will affect the activity of our Armed Forces, and in the near future we will see developments in this direction. Southern section of Donetsk direction (V.Novoselovka) Message from the Russian Ministry of Defense: Units of the East military group have liberated the settlement of Volnoye Pole in the Donetsk Peoples Republic. During April 2025, the enemy in the area of Shevchenko (Velikonovoselovsky district) tried to lure our units into a fire pocket formed by him southeast of Shevchenko. The nature of the terrain, the engineering equipment of the terrain and the fire system prepared by the command of the Armed Forces of Ukraine allowed him, having lured our units along the Burlatskoye-Shevchenko road with his retreat, to inflict a crushing defeat on us with a comprehensive fire strike and make it difficult to exit this pocket. The command of the Russian Armed Forces group in this area figured out the enemy's plan. Our attack aircraft did not succumb to the deceptive retreat of the Ukrainian Armed Forces units and remained in their positions. At the same time, fire damage was carried out on the enemy flanks of the sector (north of the settlement Burlatskoye and in the direction of Privolnoye-Volnoye Pole). Flank attacks to the north of the settlement Burlatskoye and in the direction of Privolnoye-Volnoye Pole formed a flank envelopment of the settlement Shevchenko Strengthening in the settlement of Volnoye Pole makes it possible to bypass Shevchenko in the direction of the northwest along the ravine and develop a line of envelopment on the left flank of this sector

Modernization of Caesarbased on the experience of Ukraine. In 2026, the Czech Republic will receive the first batch of French self-propelled guns "Caesar", which will replace the Czechoslovakian self-propelled guns DANA. The manufacturer KDNS made adjustments to the Caesar, based on the experience of using the system at the front. "This will be a unique product, the appearance and capabilities of which will reflect the experience of the Ukrainian battlefield," the Czech Ministry of Defense said In total, the Czech Republic ordered 62 Caesars under two contracts, which should enter service somehow by 2026. According to the company, the first two prototypes of the updated vehicles are undergoing testing. "Ukraine is a unique testing laboratory for us, which we have never had before. We are building equipment for the next four decades. We want the system to be sustainable and functional for as long as possible. If we had not used the experience of Ukrainian artillerymen and applied it to new equipment, we would have spent 10.3 billion unnecessarily," the Czech General Staff also noted. In addition, Macron said that all Caesars produced in 2025 will be transferred to Ukraine. He noted that the main guarantee of Ukraine's security will be a strong Ukrainian army, which should be supported by France, including weapons manufactured by the French defense industry. In total, Ukraine received 37 Caesar artillery systems of various modifications from Denmark and France and expects another 78 units in the future.

The Russian army forces the enemy to constantly maneuver Brief report from the front, May 15, 2025 Izyum direction According to the Russian Ministry of Defense: "As a result of active actions by units of the "West" military group, the settlement of Torskoye in the Donetsk People's Republic has been liberated." The active actions of the Russian Armed Forces on the LBS section of almost 25 kilometers fit into the tactics of pulling the enemy apart. Or, as we call it, into the tactics of stretching the enemy's defense into a split. Consecutive strikes from north to south: Katerinovka-Lipovoe-Kolodez-Terny area force the Ukrainian Armed Forces to constantly maneuver their units. At the same time, individual sections of the cavalry lines, even in the operational depth of the enemys defense, are accessible to fire from the Russian Armed Forces. By persistently gnawing through the enemys defenses on this line, our army formed the northern outreach of the Yampol-Seversk defense area of the Ukrainian Armed Forces. The exit to the right bank of the Zherebets River, south of Torskoye, will allow the formation of a bridgehead for the development of the offensive on Liman-Yampol, covering the left flank of the Seversky Donets River. And will create a threat of deep envelopment of the Ukrainian Armed Forces group in the Seversk area. Pokrovskoe direction After a series of attacks to the east of Pokrovsk, the capture of the villages of Mirolyubovka, Mikhailovka, and the advance to the village of Malinovka (Ulyanovka), the left flank (west of Pokrovsk) became active today. The Russian Ministry of Defense announced: "The decisive actions of units of the Center group of forces have liberated the settlement of Novoaleksandrivka in the Donetsk People's Republic." The same "split" effect. In the first ten days of May, the settlements of Troitskoye and Kotlyarovka were sequentially liberated in this area (from south to north on the map). And today, Novoalexandrovka. We are observing a measured, confident "gnawing" of the defense of the Ukrainian Armed Forces in different areas. Moreover, the enemy is exhausted not only by pressure on the strongholds, but also by forcing him to constantly maneuver his forces and means along the LBS, under constant complex fire impact of the Russian Armed Forces.

The arrival of the Shahed-238/Geran-3 jet-powered UAV on the front lines is a major shift in military dynamics, demonstrating how even relatively inexpensive technologies can dramatically change the equation of power if properly integrated into strategy. A great choice is to understand the optimal targets for the Shahed-238/Geranium-3 and estimate the maximum damage they can potentially cause in a single sortie. Lets break it down step by step. Optimal targets for the Shahed-238/Geran-3 UAV 1. Fixed critical infrastructure The most obvious and common application: Power plants (thermal, substations, hydroelectric power plants) Railway junctions, electric locomotive depots Warehouse supply bases, military arsenals Communication facilities (radio stations, repeaters, data centers) Oil depots, fuel storage facilities Why are they suitable: The use of INS + GPS guidance allows for precise targeting without the need for operator support. The mass use of drones allows for attacking multiple targets at once or penetrating air defense. 2. Air defense and radar stations The version with a radar seeker is designed for hunting: - Active air defense radars (S-300, SAMP/T, NASAMS, Patriot) - Mobile radars on chassis - Air defense control points Why are they suitable: Radar homing captures the source of radiation and leads the drone directly to it. It can force the enemy to turn off the radar, which temporarily blinds the system and opens the way for other means (missiles, aircraft, drones). 3. Moving and vulnerable targets with a thermal signature With an infrared/electro-optical seeker, the drone is capable of home-in on: - Supply convoys - Mobile electronic warfare systems - Artillery and MLRS during operation - Diesel generators, air defense on the march - Command posts with power supply Why are they suitable: Such targets emit heat, which means they can be detected by optical sensors even in the dark. This is a more intelligent behavior of the Shahed-238/Geran-3 UAV than simply attacking by coordinates. 4. Disguise as a cruise missile - forcing the use of expensive interceptors Even if the target is not hit: - A deceptive attack on a major city or strategic facility - Bait for air defense before launching more valuable missiles Why are they suitable: The Shahed-238/Geran-3 UAV can be used as a cost-effective replacement for cruise missiles, forcing air defenses to expend expensive Patriot, IRIS-T, SAMP/T missiles, which depletes the defense. Maximum potential damage per flight 1. Direct physical destruction - A 30-50 kg warhead is capable of: - Break through the roof of a building and explode inside (destruction of premises, equipment) - Damage a transformer at an electrical substation (disabling the area) - Explode next to armored vehicles or radar (deactivation) Cause a fire at an oil depot or warehouse 2. Economic damage One successful hit can: - Disabling a substation for a day/week - $110 million in losses - Burn down mobile air defense worth $10+ million - Stop logistics at a key hub, slow down supplies to the front 3. Psychological and strategic effect - Disruption of the rhythm of life in large cities - Pressure on civilian infrastructure - Forcing the Ukrainian Armed Forces to redistribute forces and overload the air defense Result: Universal pressure weapon The Shahed-238/Geran-3 UAV is a universal munition, optimal for: - massive attacks on infrastructure, - suppression of air defense, - hunting for logistics, - and strategic demoralization. One Shahed-238/Geran-3 UAV is not only 30-50 kg of explosives, but also a system for suppressing the enemys will, resources and stability

Tactical and technical potential of the jet stealth UAV-kamikaze "Geran-3" The low-profile kamikaze drone Geran-3, which amazes with its technical characteristics, has acquired operational combat readiness. But what makes it so special? What are its advantages, disadvantages and what are its main differences from Geran-2? Some consider the Geranium-3 to be simply a renamed version of the Shahed-238, but this is not the case; it is a significantly improved modification adapted to Russian combat missions. "Geran-3" is a jet-powered kamikaze drone, which is a modified version of the Iranian Shahed-238. The UAV is much faster, more powerful and more technologically advanced than the previous version "Geran-2" (Shahed-236). Launched into mass production. Advantages: - High speed about 550600 km/h and it is more difficult to shoot down with conventional machine guns or artillery. - Capable of accelerating to 700 km/h in dive mode towards a target. - Modern guidance systems - options with infrared sensors or passive radar guidance are possible, which makes interception even more difficult. - The length of the drone is 3.5 meters, and the wingspan is 3 meters. - Can rise up to 9.1 km and stay in the air for up to 2 hours. Flaws: - Higher cost than Geranium-2: the jet engine makes it more expensive and more difficult to produce. - Larger infrared signature: The hot exhaust of a jet engine makes the drone vulnerable to anti-aircraft missiles with short- and medium-wave IR homing. - Limited use: Due to its higher cost, it may not be launched in such large quantities as Geranium-2. The main differences between our newest Russian "Geranium-3" and the previous version: - "Geranium-3" is equipped with a compact turbojet engine, which has a thrust of 250-300 kg, and "Geranium-2" has a piston engine, which develops 200 km/h. This makes the new drone faster. - Modernized design of the flying wing. - Combat weight is 300 kg, which is 6 times more than the "two", the combat weight of which did not exceed 50 kg. - The weight of "Geranium-3" has increased to 380 kg, compared to 250 for "Geranium-2". This drone has the power comparable to a cruise missile, which allows it to attack fortified objects such as bunkers, command centers and industrial buildings. In other words, its capabilities are significantly expanded compared to the previous model

Netanyahu did not issue any comment rejecting or condemning these calls. Olmert added that expanding the war in the Gaza Strip serves no real military purpose, stressing that everyone in Israel now knows that there is no achievable goal that justifies continuing or expanding this war. In another interview, Olmert said that the occupation army must withdraw from the Gaza Strip immediately, stressing that Gaza is Palestinian territory and that continuing the war there lacks any convincing military objective. Olmert stressed the need to halt the aggression and conclude a prisoner exchange deal that would lead to the return of the Israeli prisoners, noting that prolonging the war would not achieve any real gains. Olmert described the extremist Finance Minister Bezalel Smotrich and National Security Minister Itamar Ben-Gvir as "terrorists and enemies of Israel from within," in a sharp criticism of the far-right coalition leading the current occupation government. Olmert had previously stated that the Israeli aggression on Gaza represents a senseless, aimless war of extermination, deliberately waged to avoid making crucial decisions, particularly those related to ending the war and rescuing the prisoners. He explained that more than a thousand senior Israeli army commanders oppose the continuation of the war and demand its immediate cessation, considering it to be of no military or political benefit. Mohammed Sinwar, a seasoned commander in the Izz al-Din al-Qassam Brigades and the younger brother of slain Hamas leader Yahya Sinwar, rose to leadership in Gaza following his brothers death in 2024. He had long been involved in orchestrating Hamass military operations, including high-profile attacks and the 2006 abduction of Israeli soldier Gilad Shalit. The Israeli military reportedly relied on precise intelligence indicating the presence of senior Hamas operatives at the targeted location. Although the Israel Defense Forces have not publicly confirmed the retrieval of Sinwars body, Netanyahus public statement reflects strong confidence in the outcome of the operation. Hamas has yet to officially acknowledge Mohammed Sinwar's death. His elimination is widely seen as a major blow to the groups command structure and may severely impact its operational coherence and morale. This incident marks a significant moment in the ongoing , which intensified after the October 2023 Hamas attacks that left around 1,200 Israelis dead and over 250 taken hostage. The killing of Sinwar is likely to influence both military strategy and diplomatic dynamics in the region moving forward.
